    {"parentUuid":"852773ee-c68a-4e88-ac99-64243e01830f","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"23bb175c-8a29-4cbf-b6e6-e4004bb5996a","agentId":"a259b7a17298ee935","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CrdrURp7a6XmybEnaAcknw","type":"tool_result","content":"# Analytic Computation of π(x): Methods and Results\n\n## Historical Development\n\nThe field originated with Bernhard Riemann's explicit formula using zeros of the Riemann zeta function. However, \"calculating zeros of the Riemann zeta function by hand is much harder than finding prime numbers.\" Over a century later, Riesel and Göhl investigated this approach, but encountered slow convergence issues.\n\n## Major Methodological Advances\n\n**Lagarias-Odlyzko Method**: This breakthrough used Perron's formula with a modified kernel function, achieving \"an O(x^(1/2+ε))-algorithm (both for memory and time)\" to calculate π(x). However, the implied constant was expected to be prohibitively large, preventing practical implementation.\n\n**Galway's Improvements**: He introduced an alternative kernel function to accelerate integral convergence and employed the Atkin-Bernstein sieve to reduce space requirements for computing nearby prime powers.\n\n## Contemporary Approaches\n\n**Franke et al. (FKBJ)**: This method relies on Riemann zeta function zeros rather than numerical curve integration, based on the Weil-Barner explicit formula. They prioritize computational speed using 128-bit fixed-point arithmetic developed by Franke.\n\n**Platt's Method**: A modification of Galway's approach emphasizing rigor through interval arithmetic and multiple precision libraries, eliminating formal error analysis requirements.\n\n## Computational Achievements\n\n- π(10^24) first computed by FKBJ (conditionally), later verified unconditionally by Platt\n- π(10^25) computed unconditionally using an improved Franke variant\n- Largest computed value shown in tables: π(2^80) and π(10^25)\n\nBoth modern implementations avoid traditional sieving by leveraging zeta function zeros instead."}]},"uuid":"19435474-3814-48ee-a654-be135957fdb2","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:53:10.683Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"852773ee-c68a-4e88-ac99-64243e01830f","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"b8eda664-7240-4e80-96d3-d92d6d8cf3b1","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"enumerated-hopping-pike"}
